Study

In this workflow we will analyze a data set from Nutrilip experiment

TAG and Polar lipids (PL) in Cows and Goats by (Fougre et al.2021)

Samples: 12 Cows 12 Goats

4 diets (CTL, COS, MAP, HOP), 48 samples poled by period and diet, 3 animals per period and diet finally obtention of 16 samples and 3 mL of milk per sample. Treatments: Both cows and goats were feed with the 4 treatments over 28-d applying the Latin square design. (Table 2). CTL milk was dominated by molecular species of TAG with 36 to 52 carbons, 93% for cows and 94% for goats. Saturated, monosaturated and PUFA (poly-unsaturated fatty acids) TAG were founded in similar amounts in milk for both ruminant species 33%, 34%, 39% for cows and 37%, 32% 31% for goats.

CTL: based in corn 53.2% concentrate DM, soy 13.8%, dehydrated alphalpha 27.5%, cane molasses 3.7%, dicalcium vitamin 0.2%. COS: Corn oil and Starch; MAP: Marine algae powder. HOP: Hydrogenated palm oil.

The data used are previously imputed and normalized by Log2

Data preparation

The code below shows the data set from the experiment AQ664-Nutrilip, the aim is to statistically analyze the data whit the bioinformatic tool Lipir

Import datasets from AQ664_Results_Lait.xlsx

#import data set 
data_clin_cow <- read.csv("data_clin_cow.csv",sep=',')
data_matrix_cow=read.csv("data_matrix_cow.csv")

rownames(data_matrix_cow)=data_matrix_cow[,1]
data_matrix_cow=data_matrix_cow[,-1]

colnames(data_matrix_cow)=gsub('\\.', "-", colnames(data_matrix_cow))

d <- as_lipidomics_experiment(data_matrix_cow)
d <- add_sample_annotation(d, data_clin_cow)

Data quality check

To ensure the quality of the data we take a look at total lipid intensity as bar chart or distribution of samples as a box-plot. It should be noted that our data were previously imputed and normalized with a log2 transformation, so a good quality of data will be observed.

plot_samples(d, type = "tic", log = TRUE)

plot_samples(d, "boxplot")

plot_lipidclass(d, "boxplot")

Multivariate analysis

PCA

mvaresults = mva(d, measure="Area", method="PCA")
plot_mva(mvaresults, color_by="diet", components = c(1,2))

In the PCA graph we can see that there four clusters, the COS nutritional regimes in red and MAP in purple are well defined, however we observe that the regimens CTL and MAP are not well separated and we observe a mix between them.

Orthogonal multivariate analysis

OPLS and OPLS-DA can be performed to determine which lipids are associated with a group (y-variable) of interest.

Differential analysis

# Analyse comparaison
de_results <- de_analysis(
  d,
  COS-CTL,
  MAP-CTL,
  HPO - CTL, 
  measure = "Area"
)

#significant lipids
sig_lipids <- significant_molecules(de_results)


# volcano plot sig lipids 
plot_results_volcano(de_results)

Export significant lipids

write.csv(sig_lipids$`COS - CTL`,file="Sig_COS_CTL.csv",
          row.names=FALSE)

write.csv(sig_lipids$`MAP - CTL`,file="Sig_MAP_CTL.csv",
          row.names=FALSE)

write.csv(sig_lipids$`MAP - CTL`,file="Sig_HPO_CTL.csv",
          row.names=FALSE)

Enrichment analysis

lipidr automatically generates sets of lipids based on lipid class, total chain length and unsaturation. Measured lipids are then ranked by their fold change, or p-value using results from differential analysis.in this case we use the Fold change as a parametre

#sets of libid based on it lipid class
enrich_results = lsea(de_results, rank.by = "logFC")
## Warning in fgseaMultilevel(pathways = pathways, stats = stats, minSize =
## minSize, : For some of the pathways the P-values were likely overestimated. For
## such pathways log2err is set to NA.
significant_lipidsets(enrich_results)
## $`COS - CTL`
##  [1] "Class_TG"    "total_cs_0"  "Class_PC"    "total_cl_34" "Class_SM"   
##  [6] "total_cl_36" "total_cl_44" "Class_Cer"   "total_cs_2"  "total_cl_48"
## [11] "total_cl_46"
## 
## $`HPO - CTL`
## [1] "Class_TG"   "Class_Cer"  "total_cs_1"
## 
## $`MAP - CTL`
## [1] "total_cl_40" "total_cs_1"  "total_cs_6"
#enrichment analysis by lipid class
plot_enrichment(de_results, significant_lipidsets(enrich_results), annotation="class")

We can observe in the graphics that according with the lipid class, COS and HPO have a significant enrichment in relation with the control

#enrichment analysis by chain unsaturation
plot_enrichment(de_results, significant_lipidsets(enrich_results), annotation="unsat")

We can observe in the graphics that according with the total chain un-saturation the 3 nutritional regiments have a significant enrichment in relation with the control

#enrichment by chain lenght
plot_enrichment(de_results, significant_lipidsets(enrich_results), annotation="length")

We can observe in the graphics that according with the total chain length the nutritional regiments COS and MAP have a significant enrichment in relation with the control

Contrast analyse

#results chain distribution

#results COS - CTL
plot_chain_distribution(de_results,contrast="COS - CTL", measure = "logFC")

#results MAP - CTL
plot_chain_distribution(de_results,contrast="MAP - CTL")

#results HPO -  CTL 
plot_chain_distribution(de_results,contrast="HPO - CTL")

Plot fold changes of lipids per class showing total chain lengths and unsaturations. Number on the plot indicate multiple lipids measured with the same chain properties.

#lipid chain analysis
plot_trend(de_results)
